00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:47.920
And then I want to
tell you a little bit

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:50.260
about why I wrote the book.

00:04:50.260 --> 00:04:53.400
And as Charlie said, I'm
a behavioral scientist

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:54.260
by discipline.

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:56.790
And that means
that I investigate

00:04:56.790 --> 00:05:01.220
human behavior and the
dynamics of groups.

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:03.440
I'm rather fascinated by it.

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:07.470
And I always want
to understand why

00:05:07.470 --> 00:05:12.510
there are some people in this
world that can take what is

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:17.430
and what if and turn
it into what can be.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:22.090
And I try to see, well, how
do we replicate these people,

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:23.405
how do we clone these people?

00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:30.290
You might have been able
to tell from my accent,

00:05:30.290 --> 00:05:33.930
I am from New York, born
and bred in New York City.

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:37.760
And I'm slowing down
my speech on purpose.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:40.560
But remember, because
I'm from New York,

00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:46.200
I have extreme license to
mispronounce anything I want.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:50.060
So if I mispronounce
it, go with me.

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:56.476
So many years ago, there was
a citizen protection group,

00:05:56.476 --> 00:06:02.540
unarmed, that started in 1978,
called the Guardian Angels.

00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:09.430
Does anybody remember what
a Guardian Angel-- Thanks,

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:11.760
people around my age here.

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:13.770
And I'm actually sad
that you don't know.

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:14.410
It was a group.

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:18.510
And they wore red
berets and red jackets.

00:06:18.510 --> 00:06:22.220
And they started to patrol the
New York City subway system,

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:26.640
because they felt that
it was getting dangerous

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:28.510
and people were
unprotected there.

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:30.660
There weren't enough police.

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:36.800
And they decided as a citizens
group to do something about it.

00:06:36.800 --> 00:06:41.150
They have now spread to 15
countries and 144 cities

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:41.820
in the world.

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:45.450
And they started in the
New York City subways.

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:49.410
I was fascinated by
this as a young girl,

00:06:49.410 --> 00:06:54.162
because who were these people
that went out of the box?

00:06:54.162 --> 00:06:55.370
They stood out from the norm.

00:06:55.370 --> 00:06:58.950
They actually did something
about subway violence

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:02.280
that nobody else
was willing to do.

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:06.710
And with that example, now you
sort of know what fascinates me

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:08.520
and what makes me tick.

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:12.620
So that when I found out
about Ashoka, I thought,

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:17.570
wow, here are people
that go out of the norm.

00:07:17.570 --> 00:07:20.580
Here are people that do
something for others.

00:07:20.580 --> 00:07:24.300
They totally change their
life from what they know,

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:27.560
and they do something
completely different.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:30.670
Many times they give up a
profession, a fair amount

00:07:30.670 --> 00:07:34.290
of money, because
there's something

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:37.400
that makes them
tick differently.

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:41.420
And now you know
part of why I wrote

00:07:41.420 --> 00:07:44.300
"Rippling" was because I
needed to analyze that.

00:07:44.300 --> 00:07:46.310
I needed to research it.

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:48.970
I needed to understand that.

00:07:48.970 --> 00:07:52.170
So another thing about
Ashoka that you should know,

00:07:52.170 --> 00:07:55.970
because it'll come up
later, is I describe Ashoka

00:07:55.970 --> 00:07:58.910
as a mini MacArthur
grant to people.

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:03.480
So we find the leading
people around the world

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:06.650
doing things in
social innovation.

00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:08.510
They're doing something
totally different

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:11.375
in a country that
ever was there before.

00:08:11.375 --> 00:08:15.875
Case in point and not in
the book, a woman in Egypt

00:08:15.875 --> 00:08:18.440
who has started the home
health care business.

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:20.390
Now, you know, no
big deal, right?

00:08:20.390 --> 00:08:21.450
We have it here.

00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:26.450
But in Egypt, you don't
allow a non-related woman

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:29.340
into your house to
take care of you.

00:08:29.340 --> 00:08:36.090
So to change the whole system
of elderly care in Egypt

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:39.940
was a huge deal, and we felt
it was a big enough innovation

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:42.900
to elect her as
an Ashoka Fellow.

00:08:42.900 --> 00:08:45.630
And what we do with
an Ashoka Fellow is

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:51.310
we give them three years
of a living wage stipend

00:08:51.310 --> 00:08:54.080
so that they can
say, wow, I don't

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:56.250
have to worry about
feeding my kids,

00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:59.420
I don't have to worry
about paying my house rent.

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:04.410
I could actually turn my
attention to my innovation

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:06.590
and build my organization.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:09.920
So we have now 3,000,
maybe a little more,

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:12.660
of these people around
the world, all of which

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:15.970
have gone through this
three-year period of building

00:09:15.970 --> 00:09:18.280
their organizations
and growing it.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:20.330
So by the time the
stipend is over,

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:23.380
they're kind of on their
way into an established

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:26.110
and a sustainable
idea and organization.

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:31.650
So what makes people tick?

00:09:31.650 --> 00:09:34.480
Why do people stand
out from the norm?

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.445
This is something that
I've looked at now--

00:09:40.445 --> 00:09:44.470
and I have interviewed
about 150 Fellows--

00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:46.660
and came down to 18
of them in the book.

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:48.750
And I'll explain some
of that and the criteria

00:09:48.750 --> 00:09:50.300
for it a little bit later.

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:54.870
But a picture like this may
not be abnormal to you--

00:09:54.870 --> 00:09:57.900
which, by the way, you realize
that everybody in this room

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:01.390
is really not
normal, because you

00:10:01.390 --> 00:10:05.660
live in a bit of an
abnormal world, not so much

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:09.090
as Google, not so much
in Silicon Valley,

00:10:09.090 --> 00:10:11.410
but-- because I lived here
in California for 10 years,

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:15.470
I can say this-- you live in
one of the more progressive--

00:10:15.470 --> 00:10:18.470
probably, let's face it,
the most progressive state

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:19.870
in the country.

00:10:19.870 --> 00:10:23.540
And you have a whole
different culture

00:10:23.540 --> 00:10:24.940
and a whole different idea.

00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:28.410
I mean, even today
we were at lunch,

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:31.370
and it took me
about five minutes

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:34.610
to figure out where
I put my food bowls,

00:10:34.610 --> 00:10:36.710
in compost and here and there.

00:10:36.710 --> 00:10:39.960
I mean, it's very different.

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:44.040
And so a picture like this
wouldn't be a big deal for you.

00:10:44.040 --> 00:10:46.190
But, do you know, I've
shown this picture before

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:48.260
at different speeches,
and it actually

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:52.240
makes people downright
uncomfortable

00:10:52.240 --> 00:10:55.240
to be out of the norm.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:58.490
But that upside-down
person is exactly what

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:00.355
a social entrepreneur is.

00:11:00.355 --> 00:11:03.390
Does anybody here
know who coined

00:11:03.390 --> 00:11:06.270
the phrase "entrepreneur?"

00:11:06.270 --> 00:11:09.960
OK, it was one of
our French neighbors,

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:14.620
in 1800, Jean-Baptiste
Say, who was

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:18.465
a French businessmen
and economist, coined

00:11:18.465 --> 00:11:19.690
the phrase "entrepreneur."

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:27.060
And he said, it's someone who
shifts an economic resource

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:33.170
from an area of lower to higher
productivity with greater

00:11:33.170 --> 00:11:35.650
yield.

00:11:35.650 --> 00:11:39.040
And the only difference between
an innovation entrepreneur

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:43.890
and a social entrepreneur is a
different resource being used

00:11:43.890 --> 00:11:47.510
and a different
outcome on the yield.

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:53.130
And 100 years later, another
economist, who, by the way,

00:11:53.130 --> 00:11:55.875
was not French but an
Austrian-American, Joseph

00:11:55.875 --> 00:12:00.330
Schumpeter added something to
the definition which I think

00:12:00.330 --> 00:12:01.960
is very important.

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:06.330
He said, an entrepreneur
is the source

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:12.840
of creative destruction
essential to the economy.

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:16.500
That one I like a lot, because
when you're an innovation

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:18.150
entrepreneur and a
social entrepreneur,

00:12:18.150 --> 00:12:20.080
you're a disrupter.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:22.430
And we are all disrupters.

00:12:22.430 --> 00:12:26.080
Somebody reminded me that a
lot of what you work in here

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:29.570
is around product
entrepreneurship

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:34.590
and around a service
surrounding a product.

00:12:34.590 --> 00:12:38.790
What you don't work in is
a change in human systems

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:40.730
development, right?

00:12:40.730 --> 00:12:45.270
So that's the big deal
between these two ends.

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:49.810
What we're disrupting is
human system development

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:52.210
for the betterment of society.

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:55.750
But again, you've got
to disrupt in order

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:58.456
to recreate and rebuild.

00:12:58.456 --> 00:13:00.800
So keep it in mind
that you're all

00:13:00.800 --> 00:13:03.610
disrupters, right
here, right now.

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:07.030
So let's have a little fun with
this and go into a brain scan.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:08.967
And this is a phrenology model.

00:13:08.967 --> 00:13:10.800
And I don't know if
you're familiar with it,

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:15.390
but it shows personality
and characteristics--

00:13:15.390 --> 00:13:21.440
and this is a mouthful--
of the proportion

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:23.350
of a person's propensities.

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:26.550
In other words, it
looks at what proportion

00:13:26.550 --> 00:13:30.480
do your character and
your personality have

00:13:30.480 --> 00:13:32.560
and where they are in the brain.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:34.060
So I did not create this.

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:36.770
Because frankly, I'm not good
enough to do this on a graphic

00:13:36.770 --> 00:13:40.060
or on a PowerPoint.

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:42.150
But I loved it when I saw it.

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:43.717
And it has nine centers.

00:13:43.717 --> 00:13:44.550
And can you read it?

00:13:44.550 --> 00:13:45.984
Everybody can read this?

00:13:45.984 --> 00:13:49.450
Look how small
the trust area is.

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:51.534
Now this, again, is an
entrepreneur, an innovation

00:13:51.534 --> 00:13:53.325
entrepreneur and not
a social entrepreneur.

00:13:53.325 --> 00:13:55.440
There's going to be a
big difference coming up.

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:59.495
The trust area is small, because
around product development

00:13:59.495 --> 00:14:02.500
there is an issue
called competition.

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:06.030
And you really don't want
to trust a lot of people

00:14:06.030 --> 00:14:08.610
and tell them your idea, because
somebody will swoop right

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:11.710
in and create it before
you've got it on the market.

00:14:11.710 --> 00:14:16.780
Also be aware of this very
small area called patience.

00:14:16.780 --> 00:14:18.724
Does that remind you
of anybody you know?

00:14:18.724 --> 00:14:19.158
AUDIENCE: Uh, huh.

00:14:19.158 --> 00:14:20.241
BEVERLY SCHWARTZ: Uh, huh.

00:14:20.241 --> 00:14:22.890
And so an entrepreneur, an
innovation entrepreneur,

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:27.920
because of this whole
competitive bubble,

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:29.630
also has very little patience.

00:14:29.630 --> 00:14:31.880
They need to get their idea out.

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:33.000
They need to implement it.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.991
And there is really not a lot
of time that they want to waste,

00:14:36.991 --> 00:14:37.490
OK?

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:43.960
But all of them, all of
the entrepreneurs I know,

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:47.940
both social and innovation,
espouse to my favorite Marcel

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:50.550
Proust quote, another
Frenchman, who

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:53.790
said, "the real
voyage of discovery

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:57.020
is not in seeking
new landscapes,

00:14:57.020 --> 00:15:00.230
but it's in seeing
with new eyes."

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:04.140
So therefore, every
entrepreneur sees

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:08.090
something slightly different
that no one else has

00:15:08.090 --> 00:15:14.390
seen before, and that's
called their innovation.

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:19.010
But here's where we start to
diverge from an innovation

00:15:19.010 --> 00:15:22.100
entrepreneur to a
social entrepreneur.

00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:27.120
Because the social entrepreneurs
come from all walks of life,

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:28.080
really phenomenal.

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:31.450
And they start out
someplace where they never

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:33.000
thought they'd end up.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.910
So in the book, I
have a truck driver.

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:44.054
I have a veterinary surgeon who
now builds rickshaws in India--

00:15:44.054 --> 00:15:45.470
here is where I
go from New York--

00:15:48.192 --> 00:15:49.066
AUDIENCE: Ergonomics.

00:15:49.066 --> 00:15:51.750
BEVERLY SCHWARTZ:
--ergonomics, thank you,

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:55.210
ergonomic rickshaws--
and has a whole system

00:15:55.210 --> 00:15:59.270
around making a rickshaw
driver feel more

00:15:59.270 --> 00:16:03.150
like a part of society,
have health insurance,

00:16:03.150 --> 00:16:04.740
have accident insurance.

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:06.990
And if you ever have been
in a rickshaw in India,

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:09.280
that's quite an accomplishment.

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:13.060
But he was a veterinary surgeon.

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:17.250
I've got a PhD
biomedical engineer.

00:16:17.250 --> 00:16:19.450
I've got another
engineer who grew up

00:16:19.450 --> 00:16:22.240
in the jungles of the Amazon.

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:26.370
I've got somebody so
self-labeled as a housewife.

00:16:26.370 --> 00:16:28.800
So they started here.

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:30.915
And something happened
on their path.

00:16:30.915 --> 00:16:31.750
What happened?

00:16:31.750 --> 00:16:32.220
FEMALE SPEAKER: Nothing.

00:16:32.220 --> 00:16:32.645
Just go on.

00:16:32.645 --> 00:16:33.690
BEVERLY SCHWARTZ: I
didn't do it, right?

00:16:33.690 --> 00:16:34.000
FEMALE SPEAKER: No.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:35.470
BEVERLY SCHWARTZ: OK, thank you.

00:16:35.470 --> 00:16:40.460
Something happened on their
path that absolutely changed

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:43.480
the trajectory of their lives.

00:16:43.480 --> 00:16:45.190
OK, maybe it was this slide.

00:16:45.190 --> 00:16:46.195
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yes.

00:16:46.195 --> 00:16:48.280
BEVERLY SCHWARTZ:
So one of the things

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:51.920
that really separates a
social entrepreneur is

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:55.600
their proclivity
towards empathy,

00:16:55.600 --> 00:17:00.260
sharing and understanding
the feelings of others.

00:17:00.260 --> 00:17:04.060
And in every single person
I interviewed for the book,

00:17:04.060 --> 00:17:06.670
this was one of the
things that really hit me.

00:17:06.670 --> 00:17:12.099
They really felt the
pain of other people.

00:17:12.099 --> 00:17:14.202
And I was pretty
shocked by that.

00:17:14.202 --> 00:17:16.760
That comes to play
a little bit later.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:20.310
So let's look about
the phrenology

00:17:20.310 --> 00:17:22.950
of a social entrepreneur and
how it's a little different.

00:17:22.950 --> 00:17:25.589
And of course, this
one I added in.

00:17:25.589 --> 00:17:27.310
Look at the trust area.

00:17:27.310 --> 00:17:31.550
It grows all the way, because
social entrepreneurs actually

00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:33.890
don't have competition in mind.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:38.870
And actually what they do
is they almost open source

00:17:38.870 --> 00:17:40.680
their innovation
to actually have

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:42.720
it improved by other people.

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:45.060
We do this all the time
with Ashoka Fellows.

00:17:45.060 --> 00:17:47.650
We put them together from
different disciplines

00:17:47.650 --> 00:17:50.530
in a room to hash out ideas.

00:17:50.530 --> 00:17:54.190
And everybody loves
everybody else's ideas.

00:17:54.190 --> 00:17:56.690
And all they have to do
is try to improve them.

00:17:56.690 --> 00:18:00.080
And nobody seems to have
a problem with that.

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:04.140
Then look at things like
the degree of empathy.

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:08.340
And they dream about a
more equitable society.

00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:11.210
Not that innovation
entrepreneurs don't, but it's

00:18:11.210 --> 00:18:13.670
not their primary motivation.

00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:17.400
In a social entrepreneur,
the primary motivation

00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:21.720
comes first, the
innovation second.

00:18:21.720 --> 00:18:24.780
It's a little bit different
in an innovation entrepreneur.

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:26.910
They think in systems change.

00:18:26.910 --> 00:18:29.610
And I'm going to demonstrate
that in a little bit.

00:18:29.610 --> 00:18:34.620
And they're willing to invest
in human capacity and value

00:18:34.620 --> 00:18:38.490
because they do
believe that everyone

00:18:38.490 --> 00:18:42.060
but everyone, no
exception, had the ability

00:18:42.060 --> 00:18:45.590
to change their
lives for the better.

00:18:45.590 --> 00:18:49.230
So one of the
visions of Ashoka is

00:18:49.230 --> 00:18:54.250
that everybody has the
power to be a changemaker

00:18:54.250 --> 00:18:57.720
and that you have the
ability, with a little help,

00:18:57.720 --> 00:18:58.940
to change your lives.

00:18:58.940 --> 00:19:01.610
And if you are a
changemaker, you

00:19:01.610 --> 00:19:03.830
are empowered to
change your life.

00:19:03.830 --> 00:19:06.910
So a little vignette
here about me.

00:19:06.910 --> 00:19:09.860
I don't think I ever
would have written

00:19:09.860 --> 00:19:13.310
my book without having
worked at Ashoka.

00:19:13.310 --> 00:19:14.780
And at the time
I wrote the book,

00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:17.600
it was a little over six
years that I was there.

00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:21.920
Because we really walk the talk.

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:25.172
As we talk about the rest
of the world changing,

00:19:25.172 --> 00:19:27.900
Ashoka doesn't hire
people that they

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:30.520
don't think are changemakers.

00:19:30.520 --> 00:19:33.230
And then you are
encouraged, in fact, it's

00:19:33.230 --> 00:19:34.700
more than encouraged--
and I have

00:19:34.700 --> 00:19:39.390
a feeling this is a bit like
Google-- you are expected

00:19:39.390 --> 00:19:42.440
to make change within Ashoka.

00:19:42.440 --> 00:19:45.690
Now, this drives me a
little chaotic sometimes,

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:49.120
a little bazoo, because as
the global marketing director,

00:19:49.120 --> 00:19:52.470
marketing does
have sort of rules

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:56.285
that we call branding and
other rules like that,

00:19:56.285 --> 00:20:00.990
that if you're an entrepreneur
at Ashoka, a changemaker,

00:20:00.990 --> 00:20:03.980
the rules don't mean
a whole lot there.

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:05.375
You're always recreating a rule.

00:20:05.375 --> 00:20:07.170
You're always
recreating a system.

00:20:07.170 --> 00:20:10.120
But it is an actual fascinating
environment to work with.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:13.250
And then, I had a
publisher come to me,

00:20:13.250 --> 00:20:16.480
had read something else
I wrote, and he said,

00:20:16.480 --> 00:20:19.040
would you like to write a book
about social entrepreneurship,

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:23.364
because we really don't have
one in our category line?

00:20:23.364 --> 00:20:24.530
And this is a big publisher.

00:20:24.530 --> 00:20:28.260
This is Wiley, actually,
based in San Francisco.

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:31.680
And I made up some--
I'm good at this--

00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:33.726
I made up some
answer in my office

00:20:33.726 --> 00:20:35.350
because I didn't know
how to answer it,

00:20:35.350 --> 00:20:38.980
but I always wanted to
write a book, always.

00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:40.890
And it was in the
back of my mind.

00:20:40.890 --> 00:20:42.594
And so I said something.

00:20:42.594 --> 00:20:44.260
I said, you know, let
me think about it.

00:20:44.260 --> 00:20:46.640
I went home, and I
said, wait a second.

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:51.020
The hardest part of publishing
a book is getting a publisher.

00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:54.400
And I just got a
publisher and a big one.

00:20:54.400 --> 00:20:59.950
So why do I not empower
myself to write a book?

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:03.530
And that's sort of
what a changemaker does

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:04.580
and the essence of it.

00:21:04.580 --> 00:21:07.460
You empower yourself
to make change.

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:10.430
And once that happens,
change is inevitable.

00:21:13.350 --> 00:21:16.190
So I don't want to just
talk about changemakers.

00:21:16.190 --> 00:21:19.567
I want to show you a
three-minute clip about Albina

00:21:19.567 --> 00:21:25.160
Ruiz who is a Peruvian
engineer who grew up

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:27.940
in the jungles of the Amazon.

00:21:27.940 --> 00:21:31.740
And luckily for us, the Amazon
doesn't have a university.

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:39.510
So she was forced to
move to Lima in order

00:21:39.510 --> 00:21:41.440
to pursue her degree.

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:43.990
And she wanted to be an
engineer really badly, really

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:45.650
wanted to be an engineer.

00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:51.520
So Albina moved to Lima
and was pretty poor,

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:55.010
so she moved into a really
poor, dangerous area

00:21:55.010 --> 00:21:56.216
in the slums of Lima.

00:21:56.216 --> 00:21:59.390
And she was so excited
about moving to Lima,

00:21:59.390 --> 00:22:02.130
because it's a big city, and
she comes from the jungle,

00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:03.840
and this is big time.

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:05.100
And she gets there.

00:22:05.100 --> 00:22:08.070
And she is totally disappointed.

00:22:08.070 --> 00:22:13.290
Because all she can see
and all she could smell

00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:17.450
is garbage, heaps
and piles of garbage

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:19.290
all around the slums of Lima.

00:22:19.290 --> 00:22:22.710
Because no one was
picking up the trash.

00:22:22.710 --> 00:22:24.930
Now there are reasons for this.

00:22:24.930 --> 00:22:27.080
But basically one of
the things that she

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:29.750
was told when she
asked about it was

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:33.560
that the poor don't
mind being dirty.

00:22:33.560 --> 00:22:34.560
They don't care.

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:37.820
But in fact, the poor
do mind being dirty,

00:22:37.820 --> 00:22:40.120
and nobody likes to be dirty.

00:22:40.120 --> 00:22:43.160
And she decided to do
her master's thesis,

00:22:43.160 --> 00:22:46.060
her engineering degree,
around figuring out

00:22:46.060 --> 00:22:50.490
a system of collecting
garbage in the slums.

00:22:50.490 --> 00:22:53.550
I'm making it sound
easy, but it's not.

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:56.590
The slums are usually
the favelas in Brazil,

00:22:56.590 --> 00:22:59.340
the slums in any
country, they're normally

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:01.360
out of the central city,
and they're usually

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:07.950
located on hills and narrow
roads, not paved, gutted.

00:23:07.950 --> 00:23:10.360
Very hard to get
garbage trucks up there.

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:11.960
Very hard to collect garbage.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:13.650
What do you do with the garbage?

00:23:13.650 --> 00:23:16.460
At that time in Lima,
believe this or not, they

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:18.720
were dumping the
garbage in the rivers,

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:21.560
because that was encouraged
and that was the only place

00:23:21.560 --> 00:23:23.220
to dump the garbage.

00:23:23.220 --> 00:23:24.960
So she figured this out.

00:23:24.960 --> 00:23:28.650
And she started an organization
called Healthy City.

00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:30.420
And at the end of
her interview--

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:32.990
and by the way, this is
filmed by me on my Mac,

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:36.950
so it's not professional-- the
videographer said, why don't we

00:23:36.950 --> 00:23:41.480
put a little tag in this
that says filmed on location

00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:44.160
